9. BREED DATABASE
Include a built-in breed database with anxiety predisposition data. At minimum:
Dogs (top 30 breeds by popularity + "mixed"): For each breed, store: breed name, size category, common anxiety types (array of dimensions), anxiety predisposition level (low / moderate / high), 2–3 sentences of breed-specific anxiety notes.
Cats (top 15 breeds by popularity + "mixed/domestic shorthair"): Same structure.
This data populates the breed-specific sections of the report. For "Mixed / Unknown" breeds, use general anxiety guidance without breed-specific claims.
Source the breed anxiety data from publicly available veterinary behavioural literature — it doesn't need to be peer-reviewed-level precision, but it should be defensible and not fabricated. Common knowledge from veterinary sources is sufficient.

